%N A237816 n such that either 2^n + n - 3 or 2^n + n - 2 is prime.
%C A237816 Numbers of this form can be represented in the numeral system described in A235860 with n - 1 ones followed to the right by n - 1 twos or n ones followed to the right by n - 1 twos, like this: 1, 12, 112, 1122, 11122, 111222, 1111222, ... (1, 3, 4, 8, 9, 17, 18, ... in decimal) and are the least numbers that need one more digit to be represented than any of their predecessors.
%C A237816 The corresponding sequence of primes starts 3, 17, 67, 1031, 1180591620717411303491, ...
%t A237816  fQ[n_] := PrimeQ[2^n + n - If[ OddQ@ n, 2, 3]]; Select[ Range@ 30000, fQ]
%o A237816 (PARI) isok(n) = isprime(2^n + n - 3) || isprime(2^n + n - 2); \\ _Michel Marcus_, Feb 13 2014
